mines the changes in circumstances of Asian, Latino, West Indian, and African American New Yorkers, outlining how theirs have either improved or deteriorated relative to their white counterparts. The contributors also analyze how practices and policies in policing, public housing, public health, and community services have maintained racial inequality and discuss how political participation can increase social capital among city residents in order to reduce racial inequality. The book concludes by offering a compendium of practical recommendations and actions that can be implemented to address racial inequality in the city.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMinoritieszNew York (State)zNew YorkxEconomic conditions. 0aMinoritieszNew York (State)zNew YorkxSocial conditions. 0aRace discriminationzNew York (State)zNew York. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aHistory : American History. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 4aSociology : Urban Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh1 aAustensen, Maxwell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBach, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonnett, Aubrey W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowser, Benjamin P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowser, Benjamin P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurd-Sharps, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByfield, Natalie P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCordero-Guzmán, Hector R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevadutt, Chelli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g